1
00:00:06,006 --> 00:00:08,008
[lively music playing]

2
00:00:19,060 --> 00:00:21,438
[automated voice]
<i>Please take your parking ticket.</i>

3
00:00:21,521 --> 00:00:23,898
<i>Follow the appropriate sign.</i>

4
00:00:25,984 --> 00:00:27,986
[airplane roars overhead]

5
00:00:30,071 --> 00:00:32,323
[horn blares]

6
00:00:34,576 --> 00:00:36,578
[lively music continues]

7
00:00:39,122 --> 00:00:39,998
[machine bleeps]

8
00:00:41,124 --> 00:00:42,917
- Got a delivery.
- Perfect, thank you.

9
00:00:43,001 --> 00:00:44,669
- Thanks.
- There you go.

10
00:00:45,170 --> 00:00:47,630
[music softens]

11
00:00:54,054 --> 00:00:55,597
[man] Kono! Kono!

12
00:00:55,680 --> 00:00:56,890
Over here, Kono!

13
00:00:56,973 --> 00:00:59,476
Sorry I'm late. Stupid train stalled.

14
00:00:59,559 --> 00:01:01,352
- Is the guest here?
- Yeah, standing by.

15
00:01:01,436 --> 00:01:03,438
[lively music continues]

16
00:01:04,481 --> 00:01:06,608
This way.
We'll get your makeup done on the move.

17
00:01:06,691 --> 00:01:08,610
- I don't need any.
- No, we'll touch you up.

18
00:01:08,693 --> 00:01:12,030
I don't need it. It's already tight
with the interview being cut down.

19
00:01:12,739 --> 00:01:14,574
- Whoa!
- [postal worker] Oh, so sorry!

20
00:01:15,909 --> 00:01:17,327
[man] Watch where you're going!

21
00:01:17,410 --> 00:01:18,453
<i>Now we'll take a break</i>

22
00:01:18,536 --> 00:01:21,247
<i>and be right back with our weekly check-in</i>
<i>with our reporter, Kono.</i>

23
00:01:21,331 --> 00:01:23,208
THESE DAYS WITH KYOKO KONO

24
00:01:23,291 --> 00:01:25,085
One minute to showtime!

25
00:01:25,168 --> 00:01:26,586
There you are! Good morning.

26
00:01:26,669 --> 00:01:28,630
- Sorry to keep you waiting.
- I'll take that!

27
00:01:28,713 --> 00:01:30,381
[man breathes heavily]

28
00:01:30,465 --> 00:01:31,508
- Just put some on.
- Sure.

29
00:01:31,591 --> 00:01:34,010
- Put some on.
- [lively music continues]

30
00:01:35,428 --> 00:01:37,680
[man] Okay, we really need to move.
Come on.

31
00:01:44,020 --> 00:01:46,022
[music softens]

32
00:01:48,942 --> 00:01:50,693
- [exhales slowly]
- [music fades]

33
00:01:52,362 --> 00:01:54,239
[music resumes]

34
00:01:54,322 --> 00:01:57,033
- [man] Back live in ten seconds!
- I've got a package.

35
00:01:57,117 --> 00:01:59,285
[man] Eight, seven,

36
00:01:59,369 --> 00:02:03,540
six, five, four, three…

37
00:02:03,623 --> 00:02:05,834
OPEN IMMEDIATELY

38
00:02:05,917 --> 00:02:07,544
Let's kick off our Friday segment,

39
00:02:07,627 --> 00:02:10,338
bringing insights from experts
across a variety of fields,

40
00:02:10,421 --> 00:02:12,257
alongside our colleague, Kyoko Kono.

41
00:02:12,340 --> 00:02:14,843
[hosts, together]
It's "These Days with Kyoko Kono."

42
00:02:14,926 --> 00:02:16,928
[theme music playing]

43
00:02:18,721 --> 00:02:19,931
[music ends]

44
00:02:20,014 --> 00:02:21,933
Good morning and welcome. I'm Kyoko Kono.

45
00:02:22,016 --> 00:02:24,185
[woman] We'll be on this for 15 minutes.

46
00:02:24,269 --> 00:02:28,773
[Kyoko] <i>…you've been hearing the term</i>
<i>"biomass power generation" recently.</i>

47
00:02:28,857 --> 00:02:31,109
<i>You might've been wondering,</i>
<i>"What is that?"</i>

48
00:02:31,192 --> 00:02:33,653
<i>I'm speaking with someone</i>
<i>who can answer that question.</i>

49
00:02:33,736 --> 00:02:34,821
[man] Get the name ready.

50
00:02:34,904 --> 00:02:38,116
<i>He discovered a brand-new method</i>
<i>of biomass power generation.</i>

51
00:02:38,199 --> 00:02:41,870
<i>Professor Emeritus Kyugo Sano</i>
<i>from Teito University.</i>

52
00:02:41,953 --> 00:02:44,372
- [man] Go to him.
- [Kyoko] <i>We appreciate you joining us.</i>

53
00:02:44,455 --> 00:02:46,374
So what is biomass power generation

54
00:02:46,457 --> 00:02:49,002
and why has it been getting
so much attention recently

55
00:02:49,085 --> 00:02:50,545
in relation to the environment?

56
00:02:50,628 --> 00:02:52,672
Well, the word "biomass" itself

57
00:02:52,755 --> 00:02:56,301
was coined from combining the word "bio,"
meaning biological resources,

58
00:02:56,384 --> 00:02:59,762
and of course "mass",
meaning the quantity of those resources.

59
00:03:00,263 --> 00:03:02,765
We're talking about resources
that are organic,

60
00:03:02,849 --> 00:03:05,059
from things like plants and animals.

61
00:03:05,143 --> 00:03:09,731
<i>Food waste from our own homes.</i>
<i>Sewage from city sewers can also be used.</i>

62
00:03:09,814 --> 00:03:11,733
<i>The options for this waste are endless.</i>

63
00:03:11,816 --> 00:03:14,736
<i>It can be burned directly as fuel</i>
<i>or converted into biomass</i>

64
00:03:14,819 --> 00:03:16,404
for power generation.

65
00:03:16,487 --> 00:03:20,033
So it's a way of generating power
using the city's waste?

66
00:03:20,116 --> 00:03:22,202
[Sano] Yes, that's exactly what it is.

67
00:03:22,285 --> 00:03:24,120
It's very exciting because, until now,

68
00:03:24,204 --> 00:03:28,791
disposing of all the city's waste costs
an enormous amount of time and money.

69
00:03:28,875 --> 00:03:31,836
But if we were to start
using all this waste as fuel,

70
00:03:31,920 --> 00:03:36,174
we could save up to 300 million yen
per year, per facility.

71
00:03:36,257 --> 00:03:39,135
- It would be an incredible achievement.
- [low, sinister music playing]

72
00:03:39,219 --> 00:03:42,805
[Sano] Now, it wouldn't be
without its own set of challenges.

73
00:03:42,889 --> 00:03:46,142
To do it properly,
we'd need to establish a collection system

74
00:03:46,226 --> 00:03:48,102
at a local government level,

75
00:03:48,186 --> 00:03:53,233
and that would be for things
like food waste and other waste materials.

76
00:03:53,733 --> 00:03:57,695
To be honest, it's far too big a task,
so my hope is to draw more attention to it

77
00:03:57,779 --> 00:04:02,867
and eventually the nation at large
will recognize its potential.

78
00:04:03,993 --> 00:04:06,704
So it seems like
there's still a long way to go then?

79
00:04:08,581 --> 00:04:11,000
Is there a plan in place
for when the time comes?

80
00:04:12,210 --> 00:04:14,170
Much of it is still being discussed.

81
00:04:14,254 --> 00:04:15,797
Whoever wants to--

82
00:04:15,880 --> 00:04:17,632
[choking and groaning]

83
00:04:19,050 --> 00:04:19,968
P… Professor?

84
00:04:20,051 --> 00:04:21,511
[man] What the hell is going on?

85
00:04:21,594 --> 00:04:24,222
[gurgling and choking]

86
00:04:31,354 --> 00:04:33,147
- What's happening?
- Is he choking?

87
00:04:33,231 --> 00:04:34,065
[Sano grunts]

88
00:04:34,649 --> 00:04:35,942
[woman screams]

89
00:04:37,485 --> 00:04:38,486
[gasps]

90
00:04:38,987 --> 00:04:41,155
Cut to commercial, now! Get off this!

91
00:04:43,032 --> 00:04:45,326
[Sano gasping and choking]

92
00:04:46,828 --> 00:04:48,705
[dramatic music playing]

93
00:04:53,084 --> 00:04:55,461
[woman screams]

94
00:04:55,545 --> 00:04:58,131
[sinister music playing]

95
00:04:58,965 --> 00:05:01,050
[woman whimpering]

96
00:05:02,969 --> 00:05:05,596
[screams]

97
00:05:09,892 --> 00:05:12,186
[sinister music continues]

98
00:05:17,567 --> 00:05:19,777
[dark, dramatic music playing]

99
00:05:56,647 --> 00:06:01,861
HUMAN VAPOR

100
00:06:02,945 --> 00:06:04,155
[man 1] Good morning!

101
00:06:05,281 --> 00:06:09,160
- [man 2] Hey, you think you can take off…
- Hmm. There's eggshell in my soup.

102
00:06:09,243 --> 00:06:12,038
[man 2] Do you know
how much of a shit show you caused me?

103
00:06:12,121 --> 00:06:16,042
[man 1] I got into an accident on my bike.
I was in the hospital. I left a message.

104
00:06:16,125 --> 00:06:18,169
I could barely walk all week. I'm sorry.

105
00:06:18,252 --> 00:06:21,631
[man 2] Not my problem!
You're not getting paid this month.

106
00:06:21,714 --> 00:06:24,133
[man 1] What the hell? That's not fair.

107
00:06:24,217 --> 00:06:26,427
- I didn't plan to get hurt--
- Watch your mouth.

108
00:06:26,511 --> 00:06:29,847
You were scheduled to work
and didn't show. That's the bottom line.

109
00:06:29,931 --> 00:06:31,391
Maybe I'll just fire ya.

110
00:06:31,474 --> 00:06:34,268
And you'll go back to your country
for being here illegally.

111
00:06:34,352 --> 00:06:36,187
- How do ya like that?
- [man 3] Excuse me, sir.

112
00:06:39,107 --> 00:06:41,943
Yeah, what?
You got a problem with the food?

113
00:06:42,026 --> 00:06:43,945
No, sir. It's really good.

114
00:06:44,028 --> 00:06:45,029
Good.

115
00:06:45,113 --> 00:06:46,739
[man 3] But the thing is,

116
00:06:46,823 --> 00:06:48,741
I'm not paying for it.

117
00:06:51,202 --> 00:06:52,203
[man 2] Excuse me?

118
00:06:52,286 --> 00:06:55,039
It sounds as though
you're not gonna pay this gentleman,

119
00:06:55,123 --> 00:06:57,208
so there's no reason for me to pay either.

120
00:06:57,291 --> 00:06:58,709
[curious music playing]

121
00:06:58,793 --> 00:06:59,710
Palm?

122
00:07:01,003 --> 00:07:02,088
Palm.

123
00:07:02,171 --> 00:07:03,172
Palm!

124
00:07:03,673 --> 00:07:06,008
- [shouts] Palm!
- Yes, sir?

125
00:07:06,592 --> 00:07:07,885
[man 2] You know this guy?

126
00:07:08,386 --> 00:07:10,388
No, I don't. Should I, sir?

127
00:07:12,682 --> 00:07:15,935
This doesn't concern you.
You'd better stay outta my business.

128
00:07:16,811 --> 00:07:18,646
You're not welcome in my restaurant.

129
00:07:18,729 --> 00:07:21,149
I'm surprised you still have a restaurant.

130
00:07:21,649 --> 00:07:22,650
[man 2] What?

131
00:07:22,733 --> 00:07:25,653
Just by taking a quick look around,
you're violating labor laws,

132
00:07:25,736 --> 00:07:29,365
and those ingredients back there
are in violation of food sanitation laws.

133
00:07:29,449 --> 00:07:31,617
Not to mention
the tables you have outside.

134
00:07:31,701 --> 00:07:34,203
Do you have a permit
to put those out there?

135
00:07:35,204 --> 00:07:37,582
[man 2] You have no right
to talk to me like that!

136
00:07:39,041 --> 00:07:40,585
Get outta here right now!

137
00:07:40,668 --> 00:07:41,919
[man 4] Whoa, whoa.

138
00:07:43,296 --> 00:07:44,464
[grunts]

139
00:07:47,967 --> 00:07:48,885
[yells]

140
00:07:50,470 --> 00:07:53,222
[man 2 grunting]

141
00:07:53,931 --> 00:07:56,559
- Get off of me, you dick!
- [phone vibrating]

142
00:08:00,771 --> 00:08:01,939
[grunting]

143
00:08:02,023 --> 00:08:04,192
Uh, hey, you?

144
00:08:04,692 --> 00:08:06,527
Do you mind, uh, giving me a hand?

145
00:08:06,611 --> 00:08:09,155
- Uh, Palm? It's Palm, right?
- [phone vibrating]

146
00:08:09,238 --> 00:08:10,656
- [man 2 grunting]
- Palm.

147
00:08:11,324 --> 00:08:13,534
[phone ringing out]

148
00:08:13,618 --> 00:08:14,994
Hey, Okamoto, it's me.

149
00:08:15,077 --> 00:08:16,913
[Okamoto] <i>Chief? What's going on?</i>

150
00:08:16,996 --> 00:08:19,707
- [chief] <i>Where are you right now?</i>
- Grabbing some lunch.

151
00:08:20,208 --> 00:08:23,127
<i>- I need you over here right away.</i>
- What?

152
00:08:23,669 --> 00:08:26,964
- You remember I'm on suspension, right?
<i>- This came from upstairs.</i>

153
00:08:27,048 --> 00:08:29,550
<i>I'm to reinstate you</i>
<i>to the First Investigation Division,</i>

154
00:08:29,634 --> 00:08:30,885
<i>effective immediately.</i>

155
00:08:30,968 --> 00:08:32,595
<i>Head to JNT right now.</i>

156
00:08:32,678 --> 00:08:34,305
- Uh, copy that.
- [music ends]

157
00:08:38,684 --> 00:08:41,812
Hey, I just wanted to say thank you
for what you did in there.

158
00:08:41,896 --> 00:08:42,897
[Okamoto] Ah.

159
00:08:43,898 --> 00:08:47,527
You should probably find
somewhere more decent to work.

160
00:08:48,528 --> 00:08:52,073
Yeah, well, no one…
wants to hire an outsider.

161
00:08:53,491 --> 00:08:54,992
I wouldn't assume that.

162
00:08:55,493 --> 00:08:59,163
But if that's your attitude,
nothing's ever gonna change for you.

163
00:09:03,668 --> 00:09:04,502
Hmm.

164
00:09:06,128 --> 00:09:07,129
Best of luck.

165
00:09:11,050 --> 00:09:12,969
- [murmuring]
- [officer 1] Get back, please!

166
00:09:13,052 --> 00:09:15,846
[reporter] Let's scrap that piece.
This is more important.

167
00:09:15,930 --> 00:09:17,974
[tense string music droning]

168
00:09:18,057 --> 00:09:20,726
[officer 2] You can't go in there.
Sir, you need to move.

169
00:09:20,810 --> 00:09:23,062
- [Okamoto] No, it's okay.
- [chief] Okamoto.

170
00:09:24,730 --> 00:09:25,982
Took you long enough.

171
00:09:27,191 --> 00:09:28,859
I'm sorry, I got held up.

172
00:09:32,113 --> 00:09:36,534
Your suspension only lasted three months.
Gotta say, I'm impressed.

173
00:09:36,617 --> 00:09:37,827
[Okamoto] I am too.

174
00:09:39,287 --> 00:09:40,997
You gonna brief me, or, uh…?

175
00:09:41,497 --> 00:09:42,582
Yeah, well…

176
00:09:43,082 --> 00:09:45,334
It's a bit of an odd one,
to say the least.

177
00:09:45,835 --> 00:09:46,794
[Okamoto] Murder?

178
00:09:50,131 --> 00:09:51,799
[camera clicking]

179
00:10:01,225 --> 00:10:02,393
[Okamoto] What the hell?

180
00:10:02,893 --> 00:10:04,604
What happened here?

181
00:10:07,273 --> 00:10:10,234
Kyugo Sano,
Professor of Environmental Engineering,

182
00:10:10,318 --> 00:10:12,570
was giving an interview
when this happened.

183
00:10:18,409 --> 00:10:19,827
What's going on with the smoke?

184
00:10:20,911 --> 00:10:21,871
Oh!

185
00:10:26,459 --> 00:10:28,878
That wasn't all broadcast, was it?

186
00:10:29,754 --> 00:10:31,922
I mean, it was a live interview, so…

187
00:10:33,424 --> 00:10:34,717
Jesus Christ.

188
00:10:39,430 --> 00:10:41,724
- Kyoko?
- Yeah, I thought you'd notice.

189
00:10:41,807 --> 00:10:43,768
She was the one
interviewing Professor Sano

190
00:10:43,851 --> 00:10:44,935
when it all happened.

191
00:10:45,728 --> 00:10:46,812
[Okamoto sighs]

192
00:10:48,105 --> 00:10:49,440
And where is she now?

193
00:10:49,523 --> 00:10:53,361
[chief] Forensics just finished with her.
She's in the cafeteria, resting.

194
00:10:53,861 --> 00:10:54,820
Uh-huh.

195
00:10:56,906 --> 00:10:58,449
Do you wanna talk to her?

196
00:10:58,991 --> 00:11:00,993
[chief] Just be careful what you say.

197
00:11:02,244 --> 00:11:04,955
Best to not get too involved
with that reporter.

198
00:11:14,090 --> 00:11:15,925
[melancholy music playing]

199
00:11:20,262 --> 00:11:21,555
[officer] Morning, sir.

200
00:11:24,684 --> 00:11:27,269
- Cops everywhere. This is nuts.
- My wife is freaking out.

201
00:11:27,353 --> 00:11:28,854
- I wanna get home.
- Yeah.

202
00:11:32,942 --> 00:11:36,696
Hi, there. I'm Okamoto
from the Metropolitan Police Department.

203
00:11:37,613 --> 00:11:40,658
I was wondering if I could
have a few words with Ms. Kono?

204
00:11:41,158 --> 00:11:42,952
[music becomes tense]

205
00:11:46,288 --> 00:11:47,456
[sighs softly]

206
00:12:02,346 --> 00:12:03,389
You okay?

207
00:12:12,148 --> 00:12:13,274
Kenji…

208
00:12:15,651 --> 00:12:17,027
You were reinstated.

209
00:12:20,656 --> 00:12:22,491
[sighs] Mm-hmm.

210
00:12:25,244 --> 00:12:28,122
So I guess
you're in charge of this case, aren't you?

211
00:12:28,831 --> 00:12:32,543
[Okamoto] Yeah,
I guess you could say that, but…

212
00:12:33,127 --> 00:12:36,297
as you're aware, it's pretty complex,
so it's all hands on deck.

213
00:12:37,506 --> 00:12:39,508
Mm. Of course.

214
00:12:47,767 --> 00:12:49,310
Before the incident,

215
00:12:49,810 --> 00:12:53,189
was there anything unusual
about the Professor or…

216
00:12:54,106 --> 00:12:55,357
No, nothing.

217
00:12:56,525 --> 00:12:57,568
You saw the footage.

218
00:13:00,863 --> 00:13:02,990
- [rapid footsteps approaching]
- [man] Kyoko!

219
00:13:04,033 --> 00:13:05,075
It's the director.

220
00:13:05,159 --> 00:13:07,536
He's holding an emergency meeting
for the chief reporters.

221
00:13:07,620 --> 00:13:08,746
Got it, thanks.

222
00:13:10,289 --> 00:13:12,500
I've told you all I know. May I go now?

223
00:13:12,583 --> 00:13:13,709
Sure.

224
00:13:21,050 --> 00:13:22,343
[Okamoto groans]

225
00:13:22,426 --> 00:13:24,136
I'm guessing you heard that too?

226
00:13:24,220 --> 00:13:26,639
Kono's a chief reporter now, apparently.

227
00:13:29,433 --> 00:13:31,602
So she gets promoted,

228
00:13:32,102 --> 00:13:33,979
and you get the shaft.

229
00:13:35,439 --> 00:13:36,607
Sounds fair, huh?

230
00:13:37,149 --> 00:13:38,067
[Okamoto exhales]

231
00:13:40,069 --> 00:13:41,237
[Okamoto chuckles]

232
00:13:41,320 --> 00:13:43,447
Let's get back to what we're here to do.

233
00:13:43,531 --> 00:13:45,115
[detective] Where do we even start?

234
00:13:45,199 --> 00:13:47,660
[newscaster] <i>We interrupt this program</i>
<i>with breaking news.</i>

235
00:13:47,743 --> 00:13:49,411
At roughly 10 a.m. today, live on air,

236
00:13:49,495 --> 00:13:51,705
Professor Emeritus Sano
of Teito University

237
00:13:51,789 --> 00:13:54,792
suffered some sort of unexpected episode
and died.

238
00:13:55,334 --> 00:13:57,294
- [man 1] Director!
- [director] Hey!

239
00:13:57,378 --> 00:13:59,088
[indistinct chattering]

240
00:13:59,171 --> 00:14:00,214
Hey, good morning.

241
00:14:00,297 --> 00:14:03,592
Apparently, this package arrived
just before we went to air.

242
00:14:03,676 --> 00:14:05,553
[intriguing music playing]

243
00:14:07,221 --> 00:14:08,639
Are you gonna open it?

244
00:14:08,722 --> 00:14:11,725
[director] I don't know.
Who the hell knows what's in there?

245
00:14:15,980 --> 00:14:17,231
[panicked shouting]

246
00:14:22,236 --> 00:14:24,446
- Kyoko, be careful.
- [woman] What if it's a bomb?

247
00:14:29,118 --> 00:14:30,202
[Kyoko scoffs]

248
00:14:31,662 --> 00:14:33,914
- [Kyoko] That's anticlimactic.
- Let me see.

249
00:14:34,665 --> 00:14:36,667
Oh. There's a QR code.

250
00:14:37,167 --> 00:14:40,713
That's weird, but okay,
I guess we should probably scan it, right?

251
00:14:40,796 --> 00:14:44,758
Before we go scanning random QR codes
that could've been sent from terrorists,

252
00:14:44,842 --> 00:14:47,761
shouldn't we talk to the authorities?
Who knows what this is?

253
00:14:47,845 --> 00:14:49,889
Or we just find out right now?

254
00:14:50,973 --> 00:14:52,933
[intriguing music continues]

255
00:14:54,935 --> 00:14:57,730
We won't know either way
until we see what it is.

256
00:14:57,813 --> 00:15:00,316
Once we have an idea,
we'll make the call, okay?

257
00:15:08,574 --> 00:15:10,659
I got it. I'll put it on the screen.

258
00:15:10,743 --> 00:15:11,744
[man 2] Uh…

259
00:15:13,621 --> 00:15:15,372
[music fades out]

260
00:15:23,505 --> 00:15:24,798
[monotone] <i>Hello, everyone.</i>

261
00:15:25,299 --> 00:15:29,303
<i>This message is in regards to the murder</i>
<i>that transpired this morning</i>

262
00:15:29,386 --> 00:15:32,181
<i>during JNT's "I Like Mornings" segment.</i>

263
00:15:33,057 --> 00:15:34,850
<i>I orchestrated it.</i>

264
00:15:36,602 --> 00:15:38,646
[tense music playing]

265
00:15:39,855 --> 00:15:42,566
<i>It was 27 years go that I met</i>

266
00:15:43,192 --> 00:15:44,401
<i>the Professor.</i>

267
00:15:44,902 --> 00:15:46,904
<i>That's a very long time.</i>

268
00:15:48,280 --> 00:15:51,909
<i>I can only assume</i>
<i>the question that's on all your minds is</i>

269
00:15:51,992 --> 00:15:55,454
<i>why did I decide to kill Professor Sano</i>

270
00:15:56,288 --> 00:15:59,500
<i>and who exactly my next target could be.</i>

271
00:16:00,209 --> 00:16:01,710
He's planning to do more.

272
00:16:01,794 --> 00:16:05,297
[man on video] <i>This video</i>
<i>that you're all watching right now</i>

273
00:16:05,381 --> 00:16:09,510
<i>has been sent out</i>
<i>to every single major news company</i>

274
00:16:09,593 --> 00:16:10,928
<i>across Tokyo.</i>

275
00:16:11,637 --> 00:16:13,097
<i>Why did I do this?</i>

276
00:16:13,597 --> 00:16:14,515
<i>Because…</i>

277
00:16:15,224 --> 00:16:19,728
<i>tomorrow, I would like to hold</i>
<i>a press conference.</i>

278
00:16:20,229 --> 00:16:23,774
<i>I will discuss the method of the murder,</i>
<i>the reason I did it,</i>

279
00:16:24,650 --> 00:16:28,445
<i>and… what I am planning to do next.</i>

280
00:16:28,988 --> 00:16:32,074
<i>The press conference</i>
<i>will take place at Bunko Ramen.</i>

281
00:16:33,075 --> 00:16:34,785
<i>I hope to see you there.</i>

282
00:16:34,868 --> 00:16:36,829
<i>4 p.m. sharp.</i>

283
00:16:37,496 --> 00:16:38,831
<i>One last thing.</i>

284
00:16:39,331 --> 00:16:41,875
<i>I will only respond</i>
<i>to questions and comments</i>

285
00:16:41,959 --> 00:16:46,422
<i>from the media companies</i>
<i>that report this video as their top story.</i>

286
00:16:46,505 --> 00:16:48,507
<i>The choice is yours.</i>

287
00:16:50,884 --> 00:16:52,011
<i>Bye now.</i>

288
00:16:52,511 --> 00:16:55,889
<i>I'll… see you tomorrow.</i>

289
00:17:00,728 --> 00:17:02,062
[director] Hmm…

290
00:17:02,146 --> 00:17:05,607
So he sent this video
to every major media outlet?

291
00:17:06,400 --> 00:17:08,152
Looks like this guy wasn't kidding.

292
00:17:08,235 --> 00:17:11,655
Sakura TV and Ashino Newspaper
both got the video too.

293
00:17:11,739 --> 00:17:16,035
Are we sure this is even legit?
What if he's just looking for attention?

294
00:17:16,118 --> 00:17:18,370
Is it possible that some random guy

295
00:17:18,454 --> 00:17:20,873
saw it go down on TV
and is screwing with us?

296
00:17:20,956 --> 00:17:23,250
Not possible. Look at the time code.

297
00:17:23,333 --> 00:17:26,170
This video was uploaded
just after midnight this morning.

298
00:17:26,670 --> 00:17:28,714
That's before the murder occurred.

299
00:17:28,797 --> 00:17:31,550
There's a good chance
this guy was the one behind all this.

300
00:17:31,633 --> 00:17:34,553
Yeah, but that said,
are we just gonna stand here

301
00:17:34,636 --> 00:17:37,765
and do whatever
this potential psycho wants, really?

302
00:17:37,848 --> 00:17:39,683
Maru TV is about to go live
with the video!

303
00:17:39,767 --> 00:17:41,435
ETN too, it's their top story.

304
00:17:41,518 --> 00:17:42,686
Let's broadcast it.

305
00:17:44,146 --> 00:17:46,190
[sighs heavily]

306
00:17:46,273 --> 00:17:48,609
Sir, it's up to you.

307
00:17:55,282 --> 00:17:58,327
Professor Sano's murder happened
on our live broadcast this morning

308
00:17:58,410 --> 00:17:59,953
in front of the whole country.

309
00:18:00,746 --> 00:18:03,082
Isn't it our duty to find out why?

310
00:18:05,375 --> 00:18:07,628
[newscaster] Breaking news
regarding the murder

311
00:18:07,711 --> 00:18:09,421
of Professor Kyugo Sano this morning,

312
00:18:09,505 --> 00:18:11,965
that happened during a live interview
on this network.

313
00:18:12,049 --> 00:18:14,593
A man claims to be the person responsible.

314
00:18:14,676 --> 00:18:17,596
<i>In the video, the man claims</i>
<i>he was the one who orchestrated</i>

315
00:18:17,679 --> 00:18:19,473
<i>the seemingly supernatural attack…</i>

316
00:18:19,556 --> 00:18:21,725
- [woman 1] This is nuts.
- [man 1] Did you see this?

317
00:18:21,809 --> 00:18:25,187
- [woman 2] The guy died live on air.
- [man 2] What's happening?

318
00:18:26,063 --> 00:18:29,274
- [man 3] Why would they even air this?
- [student 1] Kana! Kana!

319
00:18:29,775 --> 00:18:31,944
- [student 2] Hello.
- [student 1] Did you see this?

320
00:18:32,027 --> 00:18:34,571
It happened on the Friday segment
with that reporter.

321
00:18:34,655 --> 00:18:35,989
[student 2] Play it again.

322
00:18:36,073 --> 00:18:38,659
[man] <i>Regarding the murder</i>
<i>that happened this morning…</i>

323
00:18:38,742 --> 00:18:41,036
WHO IS THE MASTERMIND
BEHIND THE INCIDENT?

324
00:18:41,120 --> 00:18:43,330
[man] <i>…I planned the whole thing</i>
<i>from the start.</i>

325
00:18:43,413 --> 00:18:45,374
<i>Okay, I'm joking, but on today's episode,</i>

326
00:18:45,457 --> 00:18:47,668
<i>I'll be breaking down</i>
<i>what the hell happened</i>

327
00:18:47,751 --> 00:18:51,255
<i>and who this mysterious psycho is</i>
<i>that can make people float!</i>

328
00:18:51,338 --> 00:18:53,090
<i>That's one hell of a magic trick!</i>

329
00:19:00,139 --> 00:19:02,349
<i>Let's recap.</i>
<i>A terrifying man releases a video</i>

330
00:19:02,432 --> 00:19:04,351
<i>claiming he can pop people like balloons!</i>

331
00:19:04,434 --> 00:19:05,853
<i>Pop! Like that!</i>

332
00:19:05,936 --> 00:19:08,814
<i>He says he'll explain the truth tomorrow</i>
<i>in a press conference he's hosting</i>

333
00:19:08,897 --> 00:19:10,315
<i>at four at a ramen shop!</i>

334
00:19:12,568 --> 00:19:14,194
[intriguing music playing]

335
00:19:14,278 --> 00:19:15,320
[sighs]

336
00:19:16,071 --> 00:19:18,657
<i>That's just the tip of the iceberg.</i>

337
00:19:18,740 --> 00:19:22,161
<i>There's so much more to this story</i>
<i>than meets the eye, folks.</i>

338
00:19:23,328 --> 00:19:24,621
[woman] <i>Give us a hint.</i>

339
00:19:24,705 --> 00:19:26,748
We all wanna know.

340
00:19:26,832 --> 00:19:28,333
[man] Ah. Curious, are you?

341
00:19:28,417 --> 00:19:30,669
I don't blame ya. Well…

342
00:19:32,045 --> 00:19:34,590
Other online channels are convinced

343
00:19:34,673 --> 00:19:37,050
that just by talking about this,
they'll go viral.

344
00:19:37,134 --> 00:19:38,510
I don't feel that way.

345
00:19:39,428 --> 00:19:40,971
Why not, you ask?

346
00:19:42,097 --> 00:19:46,560
Why do I not live and die
by the number of subscribers I have?

347
00:19:46,643 --> 00:19:48,270
'Cause that would be boring.

348
00:19:49,313 --> 00:19:53,066
[pained yelling]

349
00:19:54,776 --> 00:19:56,778
[intriguing music continues]

350
00:19:58,363 --> 00:20:02,868
FUJITA AND KAHO'S TERROR ZONE
THANK YOU FOR WATCHING!

351
00:20:02,951 --> 00:20:05,454
[man 1] Where physical evidence
is concerned,

352
00:20:05,537 --> 00:20:08,207
no fingerprints other than that
of the postal worker were found.

353
00:20:08,290 --> 00:20:11,335
We're also working as fast as we can
to identify fingerprints, footprints,

354
00:20:11,418 --> 00:20:13,670
and all other materials
found at the scene.

355
00:20:14,254 --> 00:20:17,883
Next, we have a report on this video
that's spreading like wildfire

356
00:20:17,966 --> 00:20:20,010
across all news outlets and social media.

357
00:20:20,594 --> 00:20:23,805
Yes, sir. The video is
one minute and 34 seconds long.

358
00:20:23,889 --> 00:20:26,683
We're working around the clock
to identify this man,

359
00:20:26,767 --> 00:20:29,061
but so far, we don't have any matches.

360
00:20:29,561 --> 00:20:30,646
Early on in the video,

361
00:20:30,729 --> 00:20:33,774
he claims to have met Professor Sano
27 years ago.

362
00:20:33,857 --> 00:20:37,277
We've been speaking with some
of Sano's associates from back then.

363
00:20:37,861 --> 00:20:39,863
However, nothing actionable
has come up yet.

364
00:20:40,447 --> 00:20:41,573
So basically,

365
00:20:42,074 --> 00:20:45,035
you know as much now
as you did before we got this tape?

366
00:20:45,535 --> 00:20:48,538
That's enough.
Let's move on to things we do know.

367
00:20:49,039 --> 00:20:49,915
Yes.

368
00:20:50,874 --> 00:20:54,169
We do have a report on the deceased.

369
00:20:55,420 --> 00:20:58,465
[detective] After examination
of the remains recovered at the scene,

370
00:20:58,548 --> 00:21:00,550
it's estimated that the explosion

371
00:21:00,634 --> 00:21:03,262
most likely started
in Professor Sano's lungs.

372
00:21:03,762 --> 00:21:05,264
According to the findings,

373
00:21:05,347 --> 00:21:08,350
the lungs expanded first
and then compressed the deceased's neck,

374
00:21:08,433 --> 00:21:11,520
then exploded
with considerable force from the inside.

375
00:21:12,938 --> 00:21:15,732
But hold on now. You can't be serious.

376
00:21:15,816 --> 00:21:18,944
Are you suggesting he swallowed a bomb
without even knowing it?

377
00:21:19,027 --> 00:21:21,530
There were no signs
of physical explosives.

378
00:21:21,613 --> 00:21:24,449
There were, however,
thermal injuries on the inner lung tissue,

379
00:21:24,533 --> 00:21:26,326
more consistent with chemical burns

380
00:21:26,410 --> 00:21:28,537
than those typically caused
by high temperatures.

381
00:21:28,620 --> 00:21:32,207
Are you… saying
that chemicals were involved here?

382
00:21:32,291 --> 00:21:35,043
More precise analysis is ongoing.

383
00:21:35,544 --> 00:21:39,006
But it does seem to have been caused
by some unknown substance.

384
00:21:39,506 --> 00:21:43,385
[man 2] And when can we expect the results
of this "more precise analysis"?

385
00:21:43,468 --> 00:21:45,095
The people want an answer!

386
00:21:45,178 --> 00:21:48,265
All right, let's all calm down.
We need to stay on point.

387
00:21:49,975 --> 00:21:53,937
The governor's holding a press conference
on this tomorrow evening.

388
00:21:54,730 --> 00:21:56,732
We want as much information as possible.

389
00:21:57,316 --> 00:21:59,693
Have we identified the account
that posted the video?

390
00:21:59,776 --> 00:22:03,196
About that, sir… It routes
through multiple overseas servers.

391
00:22:03,280 --> 00:22:04,948
We don't believe it can be traced.

392
00:22:05,991 --> 00:22:07,617
What about this ramen restaurant?

393
00:22:08,201 --> 00:22:10,287
Bunko Ramen is an average ramen restaurant

394
00:22:10,370 --> 00:22:12,080
on Nanahiro Street.

395
00:22:12,164 --> 00:22:14,791
There doesn't seem to be
anything noteworthy about it.

396
00:22:14,875 --> 00:22:16,835
It's small, but the area is popular.

397
00:22:16,918 --> 00:22:18,462
[man 3] I want it cornered off

398
00:22:18,545 --> 00:22:22,090
so that it's not a zoo when this guy
holds his press conference tomorrow.

399
00:22:22,174 --> 00:22:24,092
[man 4] Yes, sir. We'll get right on it.

400
00:22:25,844 --> 00:22:27,971
- All right, now then--
- [Kenji] Excuse me, sir.

401
00:22:28,472 --> 00:22:30,807
When the governor
holds his press conference,

402
00:22:30,891 --> 00:22:33,518
do you think it would be prudent
to maybe warn the people

403
00:22:33,602 --> 00:22:36,271
about the potential risk
of a chemical terrorist attack?

404
00:22:36,355 --> 00:22:39,775
After all,
the safety of the people is our priority.

405
00:22:40,942 --> 00:22:43,612
Noted. I'll tell the governor.

406
00:22:43,695 --> 00:22:45,030
That's all, thank you.

407
00:22:45,113 --> 00:22:46,323
[officer] Attention!

408
00:22:46,823 --> 00:22:48,992
Salute the superintendent general!

409
00:22:54,956 --> 00:22:56,958
[indistinct chattering]

410
00:22:58,251 --> 00:22:59,127
Okamoto.

411
00:23:01,296 --> 00:23:02,339
Got a sec?

412
00:23:07,094 --> 00:23:08,220
[supt. general groans]

413
00:23:08,970 --> 00:23:10,972
[gentle music playing]

414
00:23:11,807 --> 00:23:12,641
Here.

415
00:23:13,600 --> 00:23:15,560
I know you always forget your pack.

416
00:23:16,269 --> 00:23:17,729
What, did you quit?

417
00:23:18,688 --> 00:23:20,315
[Kenji] It's bad for your health.

418
00:23:21,733 --> 00:23:25,404
Oh, come on now.
You're starting to sound like my doctor.

419
00:23:26,029 --> 00:23:27,280
Come on, take it.

420
00:23:36,415 --> 00:23:38,041
[Kenji inhales]

421
00:23:39,501 --> 00:23:40,836
[exhales deeply]

422
00:23:42,587 --> 00:23:43,922
[exhales]

423
00:23:47,509 --> 00:23:50,637
Tell me, you dating anyone new these days?

424
00:23:50,720 --> 00:23:53,765
What? [scoffs] You seriously asking?

425
00:23:55,559 --> 00:23:56,518
Um…

426
00:23:57,477 --> 00:24:00,480
There's somebody
Chieko wants you to meet, but, uh…

427
00:24:02,732 --> 00:24:05,110
What? Are you off the market?

428
00:24:08,280 --> 00:24:10,657
You know how the game is played, Kenji.

429
00:24:10,740 --> 00:24:13,827
You wanna get ahead in this job,
you need a good wife.

430
00:24:16,830 --> 00:24:19,124
That's what my father said,
before the end.

431
00:24:19,207 --> 00:24:20,375
[supt. general] Smart man.

432
00:24:20,876 --> 00:24:23,378
Hey, weren't you the one
who introduced my parents?

433
00:24:26,673 --> 00:24:28,008
Yeah, guilty.

434
00:24:28,967 --> 00:24:31,720
[Kenji] And didn't my mother
always hate for you that?

435
00:24:32,971 --> 00:24:34,806
- She sure did.
- [Kenji laughs]

436
00:24:34,890 --> 00:24:37,225
Complained about how he never came home.

437
00:24:38,018 --> 00:24:39,227
- [Kenji sniffs]
- Yeah.

438
00:24:39,728 --> 00:24:44,733
Being a good cop rarely goes hand in hand
with being a good husband and father.

439
00:24:45,484 --> 00:24:47,527
- That's true.
- Mm-hmm.

440
00:24:49,154 --> 00:24:50,322
So you…

441
00:24:52,157 --> 00:24:55,452
look like you've gained a few pounds.
Those buttons are straining.

442
00:24:55,535 --> 00:24:56,369
Oh…

443
00:24:57,078 --> 00:24:58,997
- You think so?
- Sorry.

444
00:24:59,539 --> 00:25:01,917
Better not be, with the smoothies
I'm drinking every morning.

445
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:04,711
[laughs] Oh God, smoothies?

446
00:25:07,964 --> 00:25:10,967
Look, I know this is one hell of a case,

447
00:25:11,051 --> 00:25:14,054
but I really think you can crack it.
I need you to.

448
00:25:15,597 --> 00:25:18,308
And if there's anything I can do,
let me know.

449
00:25:18,808 --> 00:25:20,310
Will do, thanks.

450
00:25:23,480 --> 00:25:24,606
Can I ask you, though…

451
00:25:26,775 --> 00:25:29,486
why this case?
You knew I was suspended, right?

452
00:25:29,569 --> 00:25:31,112
Well, that woman,

453
00:25:31,196 --> 00:25:34,407
the one who was there when Sano died…

454
00:25:34,908 --> 00:25:36,618
You know, the reporter?

455
00:25:37,494 --> 00:25:40,413
- Kyoko Kono.
- She's the reason why.

456
00:25:42,040 --> 00:25:44,751
That woman put you through the wringer,
didn't she?

457
00:25:44,834 --> 00:25:49,297
So now… you have the opportunity
to prove you want nothing to do with her.

458
00:25:49,381 --> 00:25:51,299
That you're over the whole damn thing.

459
00:25:52,634 --> 00:25:53,843
You're welcome.

460
00:25:58,682 --> 00:25:59,516
Okay.

461
00:26:07,232 --> 00:26:08,942
[sighs]

462
00:26:16,324 --> 00:26:17,993
[exhales]

463
00:26:19,119 --> 00:26:21,538
This is, um… Sorry, what was it?

464
00:26:22,038 --> 00:26:24,541
My name is Kyoko Kono. I'm from JNT.

465
00:26:24,624 --> 00:26:25,834
Right, yes.

466
00:26:27,043 --> 00:26:28,878
So how can I help you?

467
00:26:29,379 --> 00:26:33,300
It's a request from the PR office. They're
looking to do a piece on what we do.

468
00:26:33,383 --> 00:26:34,467
5 YEARS AGO

469
00:26:34,551 --> 00:26:36,803
- It's for Police 24 Hours or something.
- Uh-huh.

470
00:26:36,886 --> 00:26:38,430
You're doing a stakeout, right?

471
00:26:38,930 --> 00:26:41,725
Go along with him
and feel free to ask whatever you want.

472
00:26:41,808 --> 00:26:44,519
- Hold on, Chief--
- [Kyoko] I appreciate you taking the time.

473
00:26:46,271 --> 00:26:47,272
[Kenji] Uh…

474
00:26:49,649 --> 00:26:50,609
Okay.

475
00:26:54,321 --> 00:26:55,280
Well, then…

476
00:26:55,780 --> 00:26:57,657
I guess we should go. [clears throat]

477
00:26:57,741 --> 00:27:00,076
[soft music playing]

478
00:27:06,249 --> 00:27:08,251
[soft music continues]

479
00:27:10,253 --> 00:27:12,255
I SAW THE NEWS.
WHAT ON EARTH IS GOING ON?

480
00:27:12,339 --> 00:27:14,007
GET IN TOUCH WHEN YOU CAN?

481
00:27:14,090 --> 00:27:16,217
THERE'S A POSSIBILITY
OF CHEMICAL TERRORISM

482
00:27:16,301 --> 00:27:18,553
DON'T COME TO THE SITE TOMORROW!
IT'S DANGEROUS

483
00:27:18,637 --> 00:27:19,929
[music fades out]

484
00:27:24,059 --> 00:27:26,061
[airplane whirring overhead]

485
00:27:39,324 --> 00:27:40,450
[sighs]

486
00:27:48,208 --> 00:27:50,210
[tense music playing]

487
00:27:51,670 --> 00:27:53,713
- [hushed chattering]
- [cameras clicking]

488
00:27:53,797 --> 00:27:57,217
TOKYO METROPOLIS

489
00:28:03,932 --> 00:28:05,308
[man] Good afternoon,

490
00:28:05,809 --> 00:28:07,727
my fellow citizens of Tokyo.

491
00:28:08,311 --> 00:28:10,689
I'm sure that, like myself,

492
00:28:11,189 --> 00:28:13,942
you were all shocked
by the events that took place yesterday,

493
00:28:14,025 --> 00:28:16,736
but please rest assured,

494
00:28:17,487 --> 00:28:20,949
the situation is under complete control.

495
00:28:21,032 --> 00:28:24,911
The Tokyo Metropolitan Government has
full confidence in our police department.

496
00:28:24,994 --> 00:28:26,746
Their top priority is your safety.

497
00:28:26,830 --> 00:28:30,208
Right now, they are dedicating
all their time and resources

498
00:28:30,291 --> 00:28:32,752
to getting to the bottom
of what transpired yesterday.

499
00:28:33,503 --> 00:28:35,922
The police department felt it appropriate

500
00:28:36,005 --> 00:28:39,968
to warn you all of the possibility
of a chemical terrorist attack.

501
00:28:40,051 --> 00:28:42,262
It is for that reason
that we have requested

502
00:28:42,345 --> 00:28:44,347
the immediate assistance
of the riot police

503
00:28:44,931 --> 00:28:47,767
at the location
of the suspect's press conference.

504
00:28:49,060 --> 00:28:50,770
My plea to the media,

505
00:28:51,563 --> 00:28:54,149
keep away from the location
of the press conference.

506
00:28:54,232 --> 00:28:56,985
<i>- Do not go near this location.</i>
- [climactic music playing]

507
00:28:57,068 --> 00:28:59,571
<i>- We cannot guarantee your safety.</i>
- [car horn beeps]

508
00:29:00,321 --> 00:29:02,574
<i>- Regarding the man in the video…</i>
- [horn beeps]

509
00:29:03,074 --> 00:29:07,579
[sighs] Really doesn't seem like anyone's
listening to Governor Miura now, does it?

510
00:29:07,662 --> 00:29:10,123
- [horn beeps]
- [press conference continues on radio]

511
00:29:10,206 --> 00:29:13,835
[detective] Get outta the way, lady,
or you'll get my bumper in your ass.

512
00:29:14,335 --> 00:29:17,380
- [officer 1] Car coming. Make room.
- [officer 2] Move! Step back.

513
00:29:17,464 --> 00:29:18,590
[detective chuckles]

514
00:29:19,090 --> 00:29:20,633
It was a joke, calm down.

515
00:29:21,134 --> 00:29:24,220
- [officer 3] Outta the way!
- [officer 4] Ma'am, get back! Move!

516
00:29:24,304 --> 00:29:28,099
[officer 5] Stand aside, right there.
Car coming through, make way!

517
00:29:28,183 --> 00:29:29,684
- Out of their way!
- [horn beeps]

518
00:29:29,768 --> 00:29:32,854
[officer 6] Please move now!
If you don't move, we'll detain you.

519
00:29:32,937 --> 00:29:34,939
[climactic music continues]

520
00:29:44,908 --> 00:29:46,910
[helicopter whirring overhead]

521
00:29:53,166 --> 00:29:55,168
[music ends]

522
00:29:55,251 --> 00:29:57,253
[indistinct chattering outside]

523
00:30:17,023 --> 00:30:19,275
[mysterious music playing]

524
00:30:21,361 --> 00:30:22,195
[sniffs]

525
00:30:41,673 --> 00:30:43,716
- Check that out.
- [detective] Got it.

526
00:30:47,929 --> 00:30:50,098
[mysterious music continues]

527
00:30:50,181 --> 00:30:51,641
[sighs]

528
00:31:00,859 --> 00:31:02,861
[indistinct chattering outside]

529
00:31:20,837 --> 00:31:22,839
[soft music playing]

530
00:31:37,562 --> 00:31:39,439
[radio DJ] <i>Good evening, night owls…</i>

531
00:31:39,522 --> 00:31:42,233
[Kenji] To be honest,
these stakeouts are a waste of time,

532
00:31:42,317 --> 00:31:44,444
so get some sleep if you're tired.

533
00:31:45,278 --> 00:31:46,696
I'm fine, thanks.

534
00:31:50,742 --> 00:31:51,868
I, uh…

535
00:31:54,287 --> 00:31:55,955
have insomnia anyway.

536
00:31:57,665 --> 00:31:58,666
So…

537
00:32:00,293 --> 00:32:02,170
it's not like I would be able to sleep.

538
00:32:03,338 --> 00:32:05,006
I'm used to staying up late.

539
00:32:07,258 --> 00:32:09,177
I heard something interesting.

540
00:32:14,182 --> 00:32:15,850
When you can't sleep,

541
00:32:16,851 --> 00:32:19,729
just put your hand
on your chest like this.

542
00:32:20,229 --> 00:32:23,358
You'll feel the rhythm of your heartbeat
and it calms you down.

543
00:32:25,777 --> 00:32:28,029
- Is that actually a thing?
- Yeah.

544
00:32:28,738 --> 00:32:30,615
I'm serious. Go on, try it.

545
00:32:33,743 --> 00:32:35,787
[DJ continues talking on radio]

546
00:32:48,800 --> 00:32:50,468
Close your eyes too.

547
00:32:56,516 --> 00:32:58,184
[Kyoko breathes slowly]

548
00:32:59,143 --> 00:33:02,146
["Ellie My Love" by Southern All Stars
playing on radio]

549
00:33:05,525 --> 00:33:06,484
See?

550
00:33:06,985 --> 00:33:08,361
Don't you feel relaxed?

551
00:33:08,861 --> 00:33:10,363
I don't know…

552
00:33:11,990 --> 00:33:13,116
[chuckles]

553
00:33:13,866 --> 00:33:16,452
Um… yeah.

554
00:33:17,578 --> 00:33:18,705
Worth a shot.

555
00:33:21,791 --> 00:33:23,001
<i>♪ Ellie ♪</i>

556
00:33:23,501 --> 00:33:25,086
<i>♪ My love ♪</i>

557
00:33:25,169 --> 00:33:28,214
<i>♪ So sweet ♪</i>

558
00:33:28,297 --> 00:33:30,299
[lyrics in Japanese]

559
00:33:37,098 --> 00:33:39,851
[Kenji hums along softly]

560
00:33:44,272 --> 00:33:45,857
What do you think of it?

561
00:33:47,775 --> 00:33:48,901
This song.

562
00:33:49,610 --> 00:33:50,737
<i>♪ Ellie ♪</i>

563
00:33:51,237 --> 00:33:52,530
<i>♪ My love… ♪</i>

564
00:33:52,613 --> 00:33:54,157
My dad liked it.

565
00:33:57,243 --> 00:33:59,245
[lyrics in Japanese]

566
00:34:00,204 --> 00:34:01,372
What about you?

567
00:34:01,456 --> 00:34:03,082
<i>♪ On my mind… ♪</i>

568
00:34:03,583 --> 00:34:05,376
[lyrics in Japanese]

569
00:34:05,460 --> 00:34:06,502
Actually…

570
00:34:09,172 --> 00:34:10,548
it's the same for me.

571
00:34:15,636 --> 00:34:16,554
Hmm.

572
00:34:17,055 --> 00:34:19,474
<i>♪ Ellie, my love… ♪</i>

573
00:34:19,557 --> 00:34:20,892
[thunder rumbles]

574
00:34:20,975 --> 00:34:22,935
[soft music playing]

575
00:34:31,694 --> 00:34:33,237
[truck horn beeps]

576
00:34:38,242 --> 00:34:40,244
[soft music continues]

577
00:34:49,253 --> 00:34:51,672
- [indistinct chattering]
- [horns beeping]

578
00:34:53,257 --> 00:34:57,095
[woman] Sorry, yeah, just through here.
Excuse me, sorry. Thank you.

579
00:34:58,221 --> 00:34:59,263
[sighs]

580
00:35:01,974 --> 00:35:04,352
[detective] Just did a sweep,
nothing unusual.

581
00:35:05,103 --> 00:35:06,104
[Kenji] Okay.

582
00:35:07,563 --> 00:35:09,440
Do you think he's really gonna show?

583
00:35:17,073 --> 00:35:18,741
Almost time, it's 3:50.

584
00:35:20,076 --> 00:35:21,494
[Kyoko inhales sharply]

585
00:35:21,577 --> 00:35:23,162
Another ten minutes.

586
00:35:25,039 --> 00:35:26,457
All we can do is wait.

587
00:35:26,541 --> 00:35:28,543
[suspenseful music playing]

588
00:35:30,086 --> 00:35:33,714
Hey, it's Nishiyama from Social Affairs.
We're about ready to broadcast.

589
00:35:33,798 --> 00:35:35,716
Okay. Yeah, please do.

590
00:35:37,552 --> 00:35:39,595
[detective] He's 25 minutes late now.

591
00:35:40,972 --> 00:35:43,015
I think the bastard was bluffing.

592
00:35:44,267 --> 00:35:48,437
Well, would you just show up
to this shit show if you were him?

593
00:35:48,521 --> 00:35:50,398
You're basically asking to get arrested.

594
00:35:51,983 --> 00:35:55,444
This is all part of some master plan.
Must be.

595
00:35:56,070 --> 00:35:58,072
[owner] How long is this gonna take, huh?

596
00:35:58,156 --> 00:36:01,325
I'm closing my business for this?!
What the hell is going on?

597
00:36:01,409 --> 00:36:04,453
Whoever this asshole is,
he's not coming, hate to break it to you!

598
00:36:04,537 --> 00:36:06,706
I better be compensated
for the business I'm losing!

599
00:36:06,789 --> 00:36:08,583
- Jesus.
- [owner] How long are we waiting?

600
00:36:08,666 --> 00:36:12,003
- You think this guy's just gonna roll in…
- The owner's having a total freak out.

601
00:36:12,086 --> 00:36:13,838
- Tatsuya, wait here.
- [owner] This is crazy!

602
00:36:13,921 --> 00:36:15,673
- Where you going?
- [woman] Hey.

603
00:36:15,756 --> 00:36:18,718
[Tatsuya] Whoa, hold on.
You can't just run off like that.

604
00:36:21,929 --> 00:36:22,805
Dammit!

605
00:36:25,474 --> 00:36:27,351
- Such bullshit!
- [Kyoko] Uh…

606
00:36:27,894 --> 00:36:29,520
Hey, excuse me.

607
00:36:30,021 --> 00:36:30,855
Oh…

608
00:36:31,564 --> 00:36:33,524
- I know you, don't I?
- Oh, um, yes.

609
00:36:34,108 --> 00:36:36,402
I'm Kyoko Kono.
You might know me from JNT.

610
00:36:36,485 --> 00:36:39,530
Oh yeah, you were there
when, um, that person exploded.

611
00:36:39,614 --> 00:36:41,240
- That was you!
- Yeah, that was me.

612
00:36:41,324 --> 00:36:42,325
Thank you.

613
00:36:42,825 --> 00:36:45,244
Even after something traumatic like that,

614
00:36:45,745 --> 00:36:48,664
we're supposed to get back out here
as though it were nothing.

615
00:36:48,748 --> 00:36:51,876
It's gotta be a tough job.
My job's pretty hard too, you know?

616
00:36:51,959 --> 00:36:54,337
You should see all the crap
I have to deal with here!

617
00:36:54,420 --> 00:36:57,965
Mondays… Mondays, I do a deep clean.
I should've done that last night, huh?

618
00:36:58,049 --> 00:36:59,133
Yeah, listen…

619
00:36:59,217 --> 00:37:01,844
Have you always run the business here?

620
00:37:03,012 --> 00:37:04,013
Huh?

621
00:37:04,096 --> 00:37:07,350
- [woman 1] Is this guy even coming?
- [woman 2] He fooled us. Bastard.

622
00:37:07,433 --> 00:37:09,518
- [woman 3] Huh?
- [woman 4] Let's get outta here.

623
00:37:09,602 --> 00:37:11,938
- [man] I left work early for this.
- [woman 5] Let's go.

624
00:37:14,065 --> 00:37:15,316
[phone buzzes]

625
00:37:17,652 --> 00:37:19,612
KYOKO KONO
1 MESSAGE

626
00:37:23,241 --> 00:37:24,492
[sighs]

627
00:37:27,745 --> 00:37:31,374
BUNKO RAMEN USED TO BE
IN A DIFFERENT LOCATION

628
00:37:31,457 --> 00:37:33,417
[suspenseful music building]

629
00:37:33,501 --> 00:37:34,502
Let's go.

630
00:37:40,883 --> 00:37:44,262
- [Tatsuya] Okay, this is it.
- [suspenseful music continues]

631
00:37:45,221 --> 00:37:46,514
[Tatsuya] Hey, hold up.

632
00:37:47,932 --> 00:37:48,891
Kyoko!

633
00:37:50,601 --> 00:37:51,978
Hang on a second!

634
00:37:52,061 --> 00:37:54,522
BUNKO RAMEN

635
00:37:54,605 --> 00:37:55,523
Jesus.

636
00:37:55,606 --> 00:37:57,733
- [music becomes unsettling]
- [rat squeaks]

637
00:38:05,741 --> 00:38:08,077
[mysterious music playing]

638
00:38:26,137 --> 00:38:28,139
[Tatsuya] Could you please wait a second?

639
00:38:28,723 --> 00:38:31,684
You can't just walk in somewhere
without asking…

640
00:38:33,602 --> 00:38:34,937
Wow!

641
00:38:35,021 --> 00:38:37,565
[mysterious music intensifies]

642
00:38:38,190 --> 00:38:40,776
[newscaster] <i>The very reporter</i>
<i>who witnessed the murder</i>

643
00:38:40,860 --> 00:38:43,988
<i>is about to go live with the man</i>
<i>claiming to be the perpetrator.</i>

644
00:38:44,071 --> 00:38:46,449
[Kyoko] <i>I'm currently sitting</i>
<i>for an exclusive interview</i>

645
00:38:46,532 --> 00:38:49,410
<i>with the man claiming to be</i>
<i>behind yesterday's on-air murder.</i>

646
00:38:49,493 --> 00:38:51,495
[mysterious music continues]

647
00:38:54,957 --> 00:38:56,959
[music fades]

648
00:39:03,924 --> 00:39:07,303
[Kyoko] Thank you for agreeing to this.
Could you introduce yourself?

649
00:39:17,521 --> 00:39:21,650
[monotone] I am someone who's been
the victim of terrible suffering.

650
00:39:23,652 --> 00:39:24,612
So,

651
00:39:25,237 --> 00:39:27,823
was Professor Sano
the cause of this suffering?

652
00:39:27,907 --> 00:39:29,950
Did you do this out of revenge?

653
00:39:30,034 --> 00:39:31,160
Yes.

654
00:39:32,745 --> 00:39:37,083
Professor Sano was murdered
due to the many crimes he committed.

655
00:39:39,502 --> 00:39:41,545
Could you tell us what he did?

656
00:39:42,046 --> 00:39:44,548
What were these alleged crimes, exactly?

657
00:39:48,803 --> 00:39:49,845
White.

658
00:39:50,846 --> 00:39:52,264
Center.

659
00:39:55,601 --> 00:39:58,104
Sorry? White Center?

660
00:39:59,897 --> 00:40:01,440
Could you tell us what that is?

661
00:40:02,233 --> 00:40:04,318
You wouldn't know about it.

662
00:40:04,819 --> 00:40:07,321
It was a very long time ago.

663
00:40:09,281 --> 00:40:11,784
The people who were involved
with White Center

664
00:40:11,867 --> 00:40:14,370
must be remembering
the crimes they committed

665
00:40:14,453 --> 00:40:16,831
and panicking as they watch this.

666
00:40:17,915 --> 00:40:20,334
And who are these people
you're talking about?

667
00:40:23,587 --> 00:40:27,299
[man] They are the ones
who control this society.

668
00:40:28,592 --> 00:40:32,721
No matter what I say here and now
or how much proof I have,

669
00:40:32,805 --> 00:40:35,641
they'll use their power
to cover up their crimes.

670
00:40:35,724 --> 00:40:37,309
JNT REPORTER'S EXCLUSIVE INTERVIEW

671
00:40:37,393 --> 00:40:39,979
MAN WHO SAYS HE KILLED PROF. SANO

672
00:40:40,813 --> 00:40:45,568
This is my solemn vow
to all those guilty souls watching this.

673
00:40:46,235 --> 00:40:48,237
I'm going to kill you all

674
00:40:49,113 --> 00:40:51,907
one by one.

675
00:40:57,580 --> 00:40:59,540
But what if they apologize?

676
00:40:59,623 --> 00:41:02,460
Admit to their wrongdoings,
make amends in some way.

677
00:41:03,127 --> 00:41:06,422
Maybe you could still reconcile this
without more bloodshed.

678
00:41:07,339 --> 00:41:09,133
[man] It's possible,

679
00:41:09,633 --> 00:41:13,512
but I highly doubt
these people would ever apologize.

680
00:41:13,596 --> 00:41:15,723
[sirens wailing]

681
00:41:18,225 --> 00:41:21,270
It seems like
this is the end of our interview.

682
00:41:21,896 --> 00:41:24,899
[officers shouting outside]

683
00:41:35,784 --> 00:41:37,161
Wait, hold on!

684
00:41:37,661 --> 00:41:39,121
Can you tell us your name?

685
00:41:39,205 --> 00:41:41,207
[low, tense music playing]

686
00:41:50,674 --> 00:41:53,135
From now on, they will call me

687
00:41:54,595 --> 00:41:56,805
the Human Vapor.

688
00:41:58,224 --> 00:42:00,226
I… I don't understand.

689
00:42:00,768 --> 00:42:02,978
[sinister music playing]

690
00:42:14,365 --> 00:42:15,699
Hey, freeze!

691
00:42:15,783 --> 00:42:17,451
Hands where I can see them!

692
00:42:17,535 --> 00:42:18,661
Now!

693
00:42:19,703 --> 00:42:20,746
Go on.

694
00:42:46,689 --> 00:42:48,524
[sinister music playing]

695
00:42:48,607 --> 00:42:50,776
[erratic hissing and sizzling]

696
00:42:57,491 --> 00:42:59,326
[concerned murmuring]

697
00:42:59,410 --> 00:43:00,536
[glass cracking]

698
00:43:07,042 --> 00:43:08,877
[shouting and screaming]

699
00:43:10,546 --> 00:43:12,840
[officers groaning and coughing]

700
00:43:14,800 --> 00:43:16,802
[sinister music continues]

701
00:43:19,888 --> 00:43:20,931
[Kenji] You all right?

702
00:43:24,435 --> 00:43:26,604
[gas hissing]

703
00:43:33,819 --> 00:43:35,821
[whooshing]

704
00:43:42,870 --> 00:43:44,663
[whooshing fades]

705
00:43:44,747 --> 00:43:45,664
[officer 1 grunts]

706
00:43:45,748 --> 00:43:47,750
[dramatic music playing]

707
00:43:48,542 --> 00:43:49,460
[officer 2 yelps]

708
00:43:53,255 --> 00:43:55,674
[officers grunting and groaning]

709
00:44:01,263 --> 00:44:03,223
[officers shouting]

710
00:44:04,933 --> 00:44:07,519
[panicked chattering]

711
00:44:07,603 --> 00:44:09,605
[dramatic music continues]

712
00:44:14,151 --> 00:44:15,861
[officers shouting]

713
00:44:18,072 --> 00:44:20,074
[officers yelling]

714
00:44:21,950 --> 00:44:23,744
[officers scream]

715
00:44:28,999 --> 00:44:31,001
[dramatic, eerie music playing]

716
00:44:46,517 --> 00:44:48,310
[whooshing]

717
00:45:03,784 --> 00:45:06,745
[dramatic music playing]

718
00:45:18,590 --> 00:45:20,843
[dramatic music intensifies]

719
00:45:24,388 --> 00:45:26,390
[music ends]

720
00:45:30,227 --> 00:45:32,438
[Human Vapor]
<i>The people involved with White Center</i>

721
00:45:32,521 --> 00:45:34,565
<i>must be remembering</i>
<i>the crimes they committed</i>

722
00:45:34,648 --> 00:45:36,608
<i>and panicking as they watch this now.</i>

723
00:45:36,692 --> 00:45:39,570
<i>This is my solemn vow</i>
<i>to all guilty parties…</i>

724
00:45:39,653 --> 00:45:41,613
MAN CALLING HIMSELF THE HUMAN VAPOR

725
00:45:41,697 --> 00:45:43,532
<i>I'm going to kill all of you,</i>

726
00:45:44,533 --> 00:45:46,702
<i>one by one.</i>

727
00:45:46,785 --> 00:45:48,579
[foreboding music playing]

728
00:45:48,662 --> 00:45:49,872
[exhales heavily]

729
00:45:51,498 --> 00:45:53,500
[dramatic orchestral music playing]
